The players strike has bothered Posta Rangers coach Sammy Omollo who is standing in at Gor for their African assignments. 

Omollo said that under the current circumstances the club should forget about  overturning the 6-0 deficit. 

“I doubt if those boys can come back to the pitch for any training session if they are not paid. The issue is tough because the club also has no money and we may end up playing with only available players who have not even trained,” said Omollo. 






Gor Mahia stand-in coach Sammy Omolo issues instructions from the touchline during their Caf Champions League preliminary round return leg against APR of Rwanda at Nyayo Stadium on December 5, 2020.
Photo credit: Sila Kiplagat | Nation Media Group

 

The ex-Kenyan international and former K’Ogalo defender however ruled out a walkover saying he is sure some players will turn up on match day. 

“Since we are the home team, I doubt if it can be a walkover. We might not train, but I know some players will sympathise and be available on match day,” he added. 

He also ruled out coaching Gor on permanent basis due to the wrangles at the club,revealing he will go back to Posta Rangers for league assignments. 

Gor doesn't have a coach and an assistant after sacking 60-year-old Brazilian Roberto Oliveira over lack of coaching papers while his assistant Patrick Odhiambo has moved to Bandari in the same capacity. 






As K’Ogalo woes deepens, CR Belouizdad are expected in the country on Sunday evening ahead of the return leg. 



